properties.Summary:

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. Total snowfall: 15 to 20 cm. Maximum wind gusts: 70 km/h. Location: Red Bay to L'Anse-au-Clair. Time span: this evening until Saturday afternoon. Remarks: Snow at times heavy will develop this evening and taper to light snow by Saturday morning. Strong northeasterly winds will develop overnight tonight and cause reduced visibilities in blowing snow. Snow and blowing snow is expected to ease Saturday afternoon. ### Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. Maximum gusts: 90 to 100 km/h. Location: Prince Edward Island. Time span: late this evening and overnight tonight. Remarks: An intense low pressure system crossing the Gulf of St. Lawrence will bring several hours of strong southwesterly winds gusting to 90 km/h over exposed areas for Queens and Kings county later this evening, followed immediately by northwesterly winds gusting to 90 or 100 km/h to the entire Island beginning near midnight tonight and diminishing by Saturday morning. ### Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to PEstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #PEStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. Total snowfall: 35 to 45 cm. Locations: northern New Brunswick. Time span: continuing this evening and ending after midnight. Remarks: Snow heavy at times will taper off to a few flurries overnight or by early Saturday morning. Total snowfall amounts of 30 to possibly 45 centimetres can be expected for most of northern New Brunswick. The snow will briefly become mixed with ice pellets over areas between Perth-Andover to Plaster Rock to Renous-Quarryville to Miramichi early this evening. Northeasterly winds are expected to gust from 80 to 100 km/h over exposed areas of the Acadian Peninsula, causing heavy blowing snow and whiteout conditions. ### Rapidly accumulating snow will make travel difficult. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Ice build-up due to freezing rain is expected or occurring. Freezing precipitation to continue this evening. Location: Prince Edward Island. Time span: this evening. Remarks: Snow mixed with freezing rain and ice pellets will continue this evening before changing back to snow overnight and finally to a few flurries Saturday morning. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots will become icy, slippery and hazardous. Ice build-up may cause tree branches to break. Freezing rain warnings are issued when rain falling in sub-zero temperatures creates ice build-up and icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to PEstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #PEStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. An intense Pacific low pressure system is tracking across Vancouver Island.
